.SH NAME
SpeechRecognition.error_event \- SpeechRecognition: error event
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]error\f[B]\f[R] event of the Web Speech API
\f[CR]SpeechRecognition\f[R] object is fired when a speech recognition
error occurs.
.SH SYNTAX
Use the event name in methods like \f[CR]addEventListener()\f[R], or set
an event handler property.
.IP
.EX
addEventListener(\(dqerror\(dq, (event) => { })

onerror = (event) => { }
.EE
.SH EVENT TYPE
A \f[CR]SpeechRecognitionErrorEvent\f[R].
Inherits from \f[CR]Event\f[R].
.SH EVENT PROPERTIES
\f[I]In addition to the properties listed below, properties from the
parent interface, \f[CI]Event\f[I], are available.\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]SpeechRecognitionErrorEvent.error\f[R] \f[I](read\-only)\f[R]
Returns the type of error raised.
.TP
\f[B]SpeechRecognitionErrorEvent.message\f[R] \f[I](read\-only)\f[R]
Returns a message describing the error in more detail.
.SH EXAMPLES
You can use the \f[CR]error\f[R] event in an \f[CR]addEventListener\f[R]
method:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] recognition = \f[B]new\f[R] webkitSpeechRecognition() || \f[B]new\f[R] SpeechRecognition();

recognition.addEventListener(\(dqerror\(dq, (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  console.error(\(gaSpeech recognition error detected: ${event.error}\(ga);
});
.EE
.PP
Or use the \f[CR]onerror\f[R] event handler property:
.IP
.EX
recognition.onerror = (event) \f[B]=>\f[R] {
  console.error(\(gaSpeech recognition error detected: ${event.error}\(ga);
};
.EE
